height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan/370861055/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan/370861055/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>") (pubDate nil "Wed, 26 May 2010 15:43:51 +0800") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/107276") (dc:creator nil "壮丽的星球") (fs:srclink nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/120960/107276") (fs:srcfeed nil "http://www.yeeyan.org/feed/latest") (fs:itemid nil "feedsky/yeeyan/~8024243/370861055/1235862"))) ("《外交政策》：吃人的矿难" "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.foreignpolicy.com/articles/2010/05/18/is_coal_more_dangerous_than_other_kinds_of_mining\">FP Explainer: Is Coal More Dangerous Than Other Kinds of Mining? - By Joshua E Keating | Foreign Policy</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/72684\">Charlie fong</a></p><p style=\"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;\"><img src=\"http://foreignpolicy.com/files/fp_uploaded_images/100518_China_tunnel_98256597josh.jpg\" alt=\"\" border=\"0\" /></p>     <blockquote>It's been a heartbreakingly tragic two months for coal. In early April, 29 coal miners were lost after an accident at West Virginia's Upper Big Branch mine in the worst U.S. mining disaster in four decades. On May 8, an explosion at a Siberia's Raspadskaya mine killed at least 66 Russian miners. China didn't have long to celebrate the rescue of 115 miners in northern China before an explosion at a mine in the country's southwest killed 21. Then on Monday, 21 miners were trapped underground by an explosion at a major mine in northern Turkey; the rescue effort is still ongoing. So, is coal mining more dangerous than other kinds of mining?</blockquote>   <p style=\"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;\">这是令人心碎的两个月，有关煤碳悲剧的两个月。4月，美国发生40年来最严重的矿难事故，29名矿工在西佛吉尼亚州矿难中丧生。5月8日，西伯利亚拉斯巴茨卡娅矿难将66名俄罗斯矿工埋葬于地下。中国北方，人们沉浸在115名矿工获救的奇迹中还未平静时，南部就传来21名矿工遇难的噩耗。紧接着，土耳其北部一处大型煤矿再出事端，21名矿工在爆炸后被困地下，施救行动还在紧张进行中......人们不禁要问，煤矿开采是否比其他类型开采更加危险？</p> <blockquote>Depends on how you look at it. Without a doubt, mining is an extremely dangerous occupation, but it's getting safer, particularly in the United States. In 2009, a record-low 34 workers were killed in mining accidents. Eighteen of those were coal miners. In the early 20th century, the numbers were typically in the thousands. This shift is due to both improved safety standards and technology as well a move away from underground mines towards surface mining and controversial mountaintop-removal mining.</blockquote>     <p style=\"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;\">而这，取决于你如何看待。毫无疑问的是，采矿是极其危险的职业，但它也在变得更加安全，在美国体现的尤为明显：2009年达到有记录以来最低：34名从业人员在采矿相关的事故中丧生，而其中18人是煤矿工人。要知道早在20世纪初叶，这个数字得在后面加上两个零还多。这种数据上的提高在于安全标准的提升和技术的进步，同时，地表开采和富有争议性的削山开采也使得地下开采也逐渐走到地上。</p> <blockquote>Statistically, coal mining remains more dangerous than other kinds of mining, but only slightly. According to the U.S. Mine Safety and Health Administration, the rate of coal-mining deaths in the United States between 2001 and 2005 was 0.15 per million production hours. For metal and non-metal (e.g. stone quarrying) mining, the average rate was 0.1. The mining sector as a whole saw a fatality rate of 34.8 per 100,000 workers compared with 128.9 for America's most dangerous job -- fishing.</blockquote>     <p style=\"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;\">数据上看，煤矿开采的危险性要高于其他类型开采，但差别微乎其微。根据美国矿业安全健康局（MSHA）提供的数据，在2001至05年，煤矿开采死亡率为每百万工作小时0.15人。至于金属以及其他非金属开采（如采石业），平均死亡率则为0.1。整个采矿行业保持的致死率为每10万人34.8人，而美国最“要命”的行业——捕鱼业，这一数据为128.9人。</p> <blockquote>In any given year, though, disasters like the Upper Big Branch explosion, which killed more coal miners than died all last year, can send fatality rates skyward. West Virginia alone has had three major mining disasters in the last decade, all caused by explosions in coal mines. The culprit in such cases is usually methane gas, which accumulates in coal beds and can explode when the bed is penetrated during mining. (Metal mines typically operate in a much smaller area and don't have explosive gasses to contend with, making mass-casualty accidents much less likely.)</blockquote>      <p style=\"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;\">对于任何一年来说，像此次超越平常年份死难人数的弗吉尼亚矿难都会使年度致死率攀上新高。在过去10年里，单西弗吉尼亚就发生过3次主要矿难，皆为煤矿爆炸引起。罪魁祸首通常是瓦斯气体，而它则通常在煤层中凝聚，当开采钻探时很容易引起爆炸。（金属开采通常在更小的区域开展，也罕有爆炸性气体，大规模伤亡也就更少）</p> <blockquote>While mining accidents remain thankfully rare in the United States, they're a disturbing fact of life in China, where safety regulations have not kept up with the country's rapid, and largely coal-powered growth. According to the Chinese government's own statistics, the country, which produces only 35 percent of the world's coal, accounts for 80 percent of the industry's fatalities. Fatalities have fallen dramatically in recent years as the government has moved to shut down smaller unregulated private mines, but an average of seven miners are still killed in China every day.</blockquote>     <p style=\"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;\">然而，比起在中国的混乱现状，美国保持了令人欣慰的矿业事故率。在中国，安全监管难以赶上大跃进般的煤碳能源需求步伐，根据政府的统计数据，本国生产了世界上35%的煤碳，却付出了80%的产业致死率。尽管近年来在关闭了许多小煤窑后致死率显著下降，但平均来讲，每天依然有7名矿工为矿业献出生命。</p> <blockquote>The human tragedy and dramatic rescues of mining accidents make for gripping media events, but most of coal's victims actually never set foot in a mine. Around 10,000 people are killed every year in the United States from exposure to pollution from coal-fired power plants, according to the U.S. National Academy of Sciences. In China, the number is likely closer to 400,000. And unlike on-the-job fatalities, that number is on the rise.</blockquote>     <p style=\"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;\">在矿难事故中上演的人类悲喜剧总能赚得媒体头条，但大多数由于煤碳造成的受害者却从未涉足于此。根据美国国家科学基金统计，每年在美国约有1万人死于火电污染等事故。而在中国，这一数据则接近40万。更不同于从业死亡率的是，这个数据一直在增长，从未被停滞。</p>   <p style=\"margin-bottom:0pt;margin-top:0pt;font-style:italic;\">致谢：西弗吉尼亚州大学矿业工程主席彭賜燈（Syd S.Peng）对此文亦有贡献</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/72684/106409#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/131629/102981?from=rss_related\">原油泄漏－泄漏啊，宝贝，还在泄漏</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/bianbin/102823?from=rss_related\">海湾石油墨西哥湾石油泄漏，将会造成更大的生态灾难</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/shian/101863?from=rss_related\">[地球大观] 钻井平台事故，泄漏原油污染墨西哥湾</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/18357/99303?from=rss_related\">【一分钟地球】让矿难不再重演</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/116907/98418?from=rss_related\">世界十大奇迹救援 中国矿工获救居首</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/370861172/yeeyan/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/72684/106409\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan/370861172/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan/370861172/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>" "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/72684/106409" (19452 51840) old 4 nil nil ((title nil "《外交政策》：吃人的矿难") (link nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/72684/106409") (created ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-05-26T07:15:12+00:00") (issued ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-05-26T07:15:12+00:00") (modified ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-05-26T07:15:12+00:00") (id ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/106409") (author ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) (name nil "Charlie fong") (uri nil "http://space.yeeyan.org/u/72684")) (content ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom") (type . "html")) "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.foreignpolicy.com/articles/2010/05/18/is_coal_more_dangerous_than_other_kinds_of_mining\">FP Explainer: Is Coal More Dangerous Than Other Kinds of Mining? - By Joshua E Keating | Foreign 